flowRoot.flowPara: Modelling the effects of selective pressures on population life history phenomena.

Each state represents the age of an organism with lifespan λ. Each timestep, individuals in each state move to the next state, with survival probability lx = 1-dx, and offspring are produced by individuals between states α and ω with litter sizes bx.

All populations have intrinsic reproductive capacities necessary to sustain and expand themselves over time. The precise nature of these capacities differs from population to population and are products their evolutionary histories. One measure of these differences is the frequency distribution of ages across the population. [1]

The following is an exercise to determine whether selective pressures, modelled as various survival functions, can drive populations toward particular demographic histories that maximize their intrinsic growth rates.
1. Cole, L. C. The Population Consequences of Life History Phenomena. The Quarterly Review of Biology 29, 103–137 (1954).
2. Williams, G. C. Adaptation and natural selection: a critique of some current evolutionary thought. (Princeton Univ. Press, 1996).

L is the survival matrix for transitoning from one generation to the next (non-zero along superdiagonal), and B is the birth matrix used to generate the the offspring that will population the 0 state. The largest eigenvalue of (L+B) corresponds to the intrinsic growth rate of the population, and its eigenvector (scaled) corresponds to the stationary frequency distribution.
